The paper deals with the problem of compression of information, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT). The focus is on communication complexity, which is a subfield of computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The paper also introduces a new family of structured graphs, which is a topic in graph theory and combinatorics (cs.DS). The use of these graphs to analyze the communication complexity involves techniques from linear programming and optimization, which are also relevant to machine learning and data analysis (cs.LG). Finally, the motivation for the paper is to gain insights into the behavior of natural languages, which is a topic in computational linguistics (cs.CL).
